2 HOUSE BILL 1292
1 Article – Criminal Procedure
2 11–928.
3 (a) The Governor’s Office of Crime Prevention and Policy shall establish and
4 sustain child advocacy centers in the State and ensure that every child in the State has
5 access to a child advocacy center.
6 (b) The child advocacy centers:
7 (1) may be based in private nonprofit organizations, local departments of
8 social services, local law enforcement agencies, or a partnership among any of these
9 entities;
10 (2) shall be developed and located to facilitate their use by alleged victims
11 residing in the surrounding areas;
12 (3) shall assist in the response to or investigation of allegations of sexual
13 crimes against children under Title 3, Subtitle 3 of the Criminal Law Article and sexual
14 abuse of minors under Title 3, Subtitle 6 of the Criminal Law Article and Title 5, Subtitle
15 7 of the Family Law Article;
16 (4) may assist in the response to or investigation of allegations of child
17 abuse and neglect under Title 3, Subtitle 6 of the Criminal Law Article and Title 5, Subtitle
18 7 of the Family Law Article and allegations of a crime of violence in the presence of a minor
19 under § 3–601.1 of the Criminal Law Article;
20 (5) shall provide a level of care that meets or exceeds the national
21 accreditation standards for child advocacy centers established by the Maryland Statewide
22 Organization for Child Advocacy Centers under subsection (d) of this section; and
23 (6) shall be included in all joint investigation procedures developed in
24 accordance with § 5–706 of the Family Law Article.
25 (c) The Governor’s Office of Crime Prevention and Policy may contract with
26 public or private nonprofit organizations to operate child advocacy centers.
27 (d) (1) The Governor’s Office of Crime Prevention and Policy shall contract
28 with a nonprofit organization that is qualified under § 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue
29 Code and represents urban, rural, and suburban child advocacy centers in the State to
30 establish a Maryland Statewide Organization for Child Advocacy Centers.
31 (2) The purpose of the Maryland Statewide Organization for Child
32 Advocacy Centers is to provide training, technical assistance, data collection, and capacity
33 building to meet local, State, and national requirements for child advocacy centers.

HOUSE BILL 1292 3
1 (3) [The] SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (4) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE
2 Maryland Statewide Organization for Child Advocacy Centers shall establish standards for
3 child advocacy centers in the State that meet national accreditation standards for child
4 advocacy centers and shall include:
5 (i) multidisciplinary teams that include representation from law
6 enforcement, prosecutors, child protective services, the medical and mental health fields,
7 and victim advocacy;
8 (ii) cultural competency and diversity;
9 (iii) forensic interviews that are neutral, fact–finding, and avoid
10 duplicative interviewing;
11 (iv) victim support and advocacy for children and caregivers,
12 including appropriate counseling, legal, and medical services or referrals;
13 (v) medical evaluations;
14 (vi) mental health services;
15 (vii) a formal case review process;
16 (viii) a case tracking, monitoring, and outcomes process;
17 (ix) organizational capacity;
18 (x) creating a child–focused setting that is comfortable, safe, and
19 private; and
20 (xi) any additional necessary standards.
21 (4) THE STANDARDS ESTABLISHED UNDER PARAGRAPH (3) OF THIS
22 SUBSECTION SHALL REQUIRE:
23 (I) AN INDIVIDUAL EMPLOYED BY OR CONTRACTED WITH A
24 CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER PROVIDING MEDICAL OR MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES AS
25 DEFINED BY NATIONAL ACCREDITATION STANDARDS AS PART OF A
26 MULTIDISCIPLINARY TEAM TO BE LICENSED OR CERTIFIED BY THE APPROPRIATE
27 HEALTH OCCUPATIONS BOARD, IF APPLICABLE, AND PROVIDE SERVICES WITHIN
28 THE SCOPE OF THE PROVIDER’S LICENSE OR CERTIFICATION OR PRACTICE UNDER
29 LAWFUL SUPERVISION AS AUTHORIZED BY STATE LAW; AND
30 (II) EACH CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER TO ESTABLISH A
31 CONTINUITY OF CARE PLAN THAT AT A MINIMUM SHALL:

4 HOUSE BILL 1292
1 1. IF KNOWN BY THE CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER AND THE
2 FORMER PROVIDER IS EMPLOYED BY OR CONTRACTED WITH THE CHILD ADVOCACY
3 CENTER, IN COMPLIANCE WITH HIPAA (HEALTH INSURANCE PORTABILITY AND
4 ACCOUNTABILITY ACT) AND APPLICABLE FEDERAL AND STATE CONFIDENTIALITY
5 LAWS, AND ONLY IF IT DOES NOT PRESENT A DANGER TO THE CHILD, PROVIDE
6 WRITTEN NOTIFICATION TO THE CHILD AND PARENT OR LEGAL GUARDIAN WHEN
7 THERE IS A CHANGE IN A PROVIDER OF MEDICAL OR MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES
8 THAT INCLUDES THE NAME AND CONTACT INFORMATION OF THE NEW PROVIDER OR
9 PRACTICE AND FORMER PROVIDER OR PRACTICE TO PROVIDE A MEANS THROUGH
10 WHICH THE CHILD AND PARENT OR LEGAL GUARDIAN CAN CONTACT THE NEW AND
11 FORMER PROVIDER; AND
12 2. SUBJECT TO ITEM 1 OF THIS ITEM, ALLOW THE
13 FORMER PROVIDER, IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE PROVIDER’S PROFESSIONAL ETHICS
14 AND STANDARDS OF CARE, TO CONTACT THE CHILD AND PARENT OR LEGAL
15 GUARDIAN TO CONDUCT A TERMINATION SESSION AND WHEN INDICATED AS
16 CLINICALLY APPROPRIATE AND PRESENTING NO ADDITIONAL RISK TO THE CHILD
17 AS DETERMINED BY THE CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER SUPERVISOR TO ASSIST IN THE
18 TRANSFER OF CARE.
19 (5) EACH CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER SHALL REPORT A COMPLAINT
20 RESULTING IN A FINDING BY CHILD PROTECTIVE SERVICES BASED ON THE
21 STANDARDS ESTABLISHED UNDER PARAGRAPH (3) OF THIS SUBSECTION TO THE
22 GOVERNOR’S OFFICE OF CRIME PREVENTION AND POLICY FOR REFERRAL TO THE
23 ATTORNEY GENERAL FOR INVESTIGATION AND FURTHER ACTION, IF NECESSARY.
24 (e) (1) Money for child advocacy centers:
25 (1) (I) shall be distributed to child advocacy centers in accordance with
26 a formula agreed on by the Maryland Statewide Organization for Child Advocacy Centers
27 and the Governor’s Office of Crime Prevention and Policy;
28 (2) (II) shall be used to supplement, not supplant, money that the
29 program receives from other sources; and
30 (3) (III) may be used to assist child advocacy centers in meeting the
31 standards under subsection (d) of this section.
32 (2) THE GOVERNOR’S OFFICE OF CRIME PREVENTION AND POLICY
33 MAY ISSUE A GRANT TO ASSIST A CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER WITH TECHNICAL
34 ASSISTANCE TO IMPLEMENT STANDARDS.

HOUSE BILL 1292 5
1 (f) (1) On or before June 1 each year, the Governor’s Office of Crime
2 Prevention and Policy shall submit an annual report, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the
3 State Government Article, on child advocacy centers to the General Assembly.
4 (2) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY JUNE 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN
5 2028, THE GOVERNOR’S OFFICE OF CRIME PREVENTION AND POLICY SHALL
6 PUBLISH ON ITS WEBSITE, FOR THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR:
7 (I) A DESCRIPTION OF THE STANDARDS FOR CHILD ADVOCACY
8 CENTERS ESTABLISHED BY THE MARYLAND STATEWIDE ORGANIZATION FOR CHILD
9 ADVOCACY CENTERS AND INFORMATION ON COMPLIANCE OF EACH CHILD
10 ADVOCACY CENTER WITH THE STANDARDS; AND
11 (II) COMPLAINT INFORMATION A SUMMARY OF COMPLAINTS
12 RELATED TO EACH COMPLIANCE OF CHILD ADVOCACY CENTER STANDARDS, IF
13 APPLICABLE, AND THE RESOLUTION OF ANY COMPLAINT RECEIVED BY THE
14 GOVERNOR’S OFFICE OF CRIME PREVENTION AND POLICY, UNLESS SUCH
15 INFORMATION IS CONFIDENTIAL OR OTHERWISE PROTECTED UNDER FEDERAL LAW.
16 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
17 October July 1, 2026.
Approved:
